The previous week had ended at 7:58 p.m., a point on the dial that marks a democracy still formally intact but under sustained pressure. At the close of Week 35, the clock remained at 7:58 p.m., with a net change of zero minutes. The stillness is deceptive. Executive power without effective oversight, law used as a weapon, federal force turned against disfavored cities, protest narrowed by \'93security,\'94 and independent media squeezed by regulators all intensified. But they did so along paths that were already open. The week did not break new ground so much as fill in the trenches that had been dug earlier. Courts and Congress did register some resistance: judges blocked certain deportations, preserved a Federal Reserve governor\'92s job, and dismissed an overreaching libel suit; lawmakers opened investigations and wrote letters. Those acts mattered. They kept the clock from jumping forward. They did not, however, restore any lost minutes.\
