Immigration enforcement became the sharpest edge of this new order. ICE raids in Los Angeles, conducted with masked agents and unmarked vehicles, swept up immigrants and people perceived to be immigrants in scenes that echoed earlier eras of mass roundups. A Supreme Court ruling cleared the way, allowing warrantless immigration raids based on skin color, accent, or job and overturning a restraining order that had slowed such operations in California. In Georgia, a Hyundai plant raid detained hundreds of Korean workers, many with valid business visas, in what officials later called an \'93operational mistake.\'94 Those workers were held in overcrowded, degrading conditions, and the arrests sparked outrage in South Korea. In Illinois, ICE\'92s Operation Midway Blitz left a man dead at a traffic stop near a school, prompting the governor and members of Congress to demand an investigation. At the same time, ICE dramatically expanded its use of solitary confinement, placing more than 10,500 people in isolation in just over a year, with vulnerable detainees held the longest. The reopening of Angola prison\'92s notorious \'93Camp J\'94 as an ICE detention site under a new name, Camp 57, completed the picture: a civil immigration system borrowing the harshest symbols and practices of criminal incarceration.\
