These were not isolated excesses. They were backed by law and by the redirection of federal capacity. The Justice Department charged healthcare workers in California with assaulting federal agents after they tried to shield a patient from ICE in a surgical center, turning medical ethics into a potential crime. ICE and DHS announced that assaulting their officers would be treated as a federal felony and broadened their definition of \'93threats\'94 to include actions like filming operations, blurring the line between oversight and obstruction. Roughly 20% of FBI agents, including nearly all of Baltimore\'92s domestic terrorism squad, were reassigned to immigration enforcement, leaving extremist groups with more room to operate. Anti\uc0\u8209 trafficking initiatives were cut back, and agents who once pursued child exploitation and terrorism were sent into worksite raids they barely understood. A federal judge in New York ordered improvements to harsh detention conditions in a Manhattan building, and another in Texas heard detailed allegations of abuse at the Dilley family center, but these interventions were remedial. They treated symptoms of a system whose core design now prioritized deportation quotas and spectacle over protection. That design was the point.\
