In the moral terms that underlie the Democracy Clock, Week 35 showed a civic covenant under strain across all six pillars. Character was bent toward loyalty and spectacle rather than service, as seen in the use of flags, medals, and House resolutions to honor a partisan activist while other victims of political violence received less attention. Ethics were compromised by the monetization of public tragedy, the UAE chip and crypto deals that blurred public duty and private gain, and the use of law to harass opponents rather than curb corruption. Restraint eroded as emergency powers became routine tools for domestic policing and as federal force was turned against cities and protesters. Truthfulness suffered under removed studies, repeated election lies, and the sidelining of scientific expertise. Good faith in democratic engagement waned as legislatures became stages for symbolic punishment and as appointments and prosecutions were openly tied to loyalty. Stewardship faltered in the gutting of environmental and labor protections and the redirection of resources away from the vulnerable toward those closest to power.\
